# Solving the Equidecomposable Problem in Lean 4

I'll tackle the problem of proving that the centerless n-sphere is equidecomposable to the full n-sphere for n ≥ 2. 

First, let me understand the problem statement. We need to show that the set of points at distance r from the origin (the n-sphere) can be partitioned into subsets such that each subset can be rotated to the corresponding subset of the full n-sphere. The key insight is that the center point needs to be handled specially because it's the only point that's not on the n-sphere.

The approach will be to construct a decomposition where we separate the center point from the rest of the n-sphere. Then, we'll define rotations that move points on the n-sphere to their correct positions, leaving the center point fixed.

